$TSLA expensive is a trend. Like luxury goods, which is supported by a market of buyers. As long as market of buyers support expensive, the expensive trend continues. Hard to reconcile with valuation indicators like P/E, but in the stock market, price trend trumps every other indicator. Therefore as long as price trend = true, it isn’t too expensive. Expensive only becomes more expensive in the stock market. Until that trend = false and is invalidated. Bullish

“An option wall refers to a large delta-adjusted open interest on a certain strike. It is simply the open interest for that strike multiplied by its delta. It is important because it tells us how many shares market makers need to buy or sell to remain delta neutral. [Market makers don’t] have a directional bias in the market and strive to remain hedged or flat. 

The mechanic of delta-neutrality is simple. For instance, if a market maker sells a call option on SPY with a delta of 0.90, it will need to buy 90 SPY shares to remain delta neutral. As the delta-adjusted open interest builds up, so does the number of shares held by market makers. When close to expiration, a large number of these call options will be sold by investors, forcing, in turn, market makers to sell their shares. [Thus], if the market is above a large call option wall, it will create selling pressure as expiration approaches. This will preclude the price from freely moving upwards.”
